Subject: NELL:everypromotedthing
Object: every promoted category instance in KB

Subject: NELL:location
Object: The Location type is used for any topic with a fixed location on the planet Earth. It includes geographic features such as oceans and mountains political entities like cities and man-made objects like buildings

Subject: NELL:attraction
Object: sight or feature that you might visit as a tourist. Examples include monuments parks museums and the like. This type includes Location which means it is usually used for things which are themselves locations (like those described above

Subject: NELL:aquarium
Object: the aquatic counterpart of a zoo housing living aquatic species for viewing

Subject: NELL:zoo
Object: facility in which animals are confined within enclosures displayed to the public and in which they may also be bred.

Subject: NELL:park
Object: Public local/state/national parks as well as amusement parks and other privately-run attractions.

Subject: NELL:monument
Object: An architectural structure (usually public) which is erected to commemorate a person place event or group.

Subject: NELL:port
Object: a location on a coast or shore containing one or more harbors where ships can dock and transfer people or cargo to or from land. Port locations are selected to optimize access to land and navigable water for commercial demand and for shelter from wind and waves. Ports with deeper water are rarer but can handle larger more economical ships. Since ports throughout history handled every kind of traffic support and storage facilities vary widely may extend for miles and dominate the local economy. Some ports have an important perhaps exclusively military role.

Subject: NELL:museum
Object: A museum is a "permanent institution in the service of society and of its development open to the public which acquires conserves researches communicates and exhibits the tangible and intangible heritage of humanity and its environment for the purposes of education study and enjoyment" as defined by the International Council of Museums.

Subject: NELL:transportation
Object: a mode of travel such as rail transport or automobile. It is a category defining a means of moving from one location to another.

Subject: NELL:stadiumoreventvenue
Object: A building where large spectator events (usually sporting events) take place.

Subject: NELL:beach
Object: geological landform along the shoreline of an ocean sea or lake. It usually consists of loose particles which are often composed of rock such as sand gravel shingle pebbles waves or cobblestones

Subject: NELL:room
Object: A conceptually-distinct subspace within a building. The entire space within a building could be considered to be a room in the case of say a one-room schoolhouse.

Subject: NELL:officebuildingroom
Object: A room designation such as would be used for rooms in an office building

Subject: NELL:geopoliticallocation
Object: Those geopolitical entities that are location

Subject: NELL:island
Object: any piece of land surrounded entirely by water

Subject: NELL:country
Object: The type "country" in Freebase can and should be used with a variety of topics. The most common will be probably be current and former independent nations potentially including composite entities such as empires. It can also be used for autonomous entities within such a composite such as the four current constituent countries (England Northern Ireland Scotland and Wales) of the United Kingdom.  Anything having an ISO country code qualifies as a country including contested countries like Taiwan and including territories of minor or no population.

Subject: NELL:stateorprovince
Object: In general the top-level administrative or political subdivision within a country.

Subject: NELL:continent
Object: A continent is a large land mass defined mostly by conventional use but closely related to tectonic plates within the earth's crust.

Subject: NELL:city
Object: City/town/village refers to all named inhabited places at the most locally recognized level but above the level of neighborhood. It is the most local region where there is a form of government or self-organization.   Cities/towns/villages are larger than neighborhoods and are typically contained within a larger administrative division such as a county department province etc. It should be noted however that large or significant cities may themselves also function as higher-level administrative divisions.   For more information please see the Freebase wiki page on City/Town/Village.

Subject: NELL:county
Object: Intermediate administrative region between state/province and local munincipal. This category also encompasses customary abberations such as the boroughs of the City of Greater New York being treated as logically equivalent to counties.

Subject: NELL:street
Object: A route of travel that has a single name indicating its entirety and that could have a street address (as distinct from trail which may not feature addresses)

Subject: NELL:cave
Object: An underground space humans or animals can enter - a cave.

Subject: NELL:zipcode
Object: US ZIP codes. Other postal codes are not allowed

Subject: NELL:planet
Object: is a celestial body orbiting a star or stellar remnant that is massive enough to be rounded by its own gravity is not massive enough to cause thermonuclear fusion and has cleared its neighbouring region of planetesimals

Subject: NELL:lake
Object: A lake is a body of water surrounded entirely by land. For the purposes of this schema any such body regardless of size should be considered a lake. This includes ponds but excludes such bodies as marshes bogs fens etc.

Subject: NELL:trail
Object: Trails for hiking walking biking or even driving.  Routes with street addresses cannot be trails.

Subject: NELL:highway
Object: is a public road especially a major road connecting two or more destinations.

Subject: NELL:river
Object: A river is a natural waterway usually formed by water derived from either precipitation or glacial meltwater and flows from higher ground to lower ground. Most commonly rivers flow on the surface but there are many examples of underground rivers. In some areas of highly variable rainfall some rivers carry water only occasionally and may be dry for several years at a time. Such waterways of all sizes including streams and creeks can be listed under this type.

Subject: NELL:website
Object: A Website or (Web site) is a collection of web pages typically common to a particular domain name or subdomain on the World Wide Web on the Internet. A web page is a document typically written in HTML that is almost always accessible via HTTP a protocol that transfers information from the website's server to display in the user's Web browser.

Subject: NELL:blog
Object: A blog (or weblog) is a user-generated website where entries are made in journal style and displayed in a reverse chronological order. Blogs often provide commentary or news on a particular subject such as food politics or local news; some function as more personal online diaries.

Subject: NELL:politicsblog
Object: A blog substantially and charactarizably but not exclusively devoted to politics or political issues.  A general current-events blog such as might be equated with a general newspaper should not be classified as a politicsBlog although an identifyable subsection or the blog of a particular staff member could be.

Subject: NELL:landscapefeatures
Object: This type captures geographical features of the Earth including landforms bodies of water underwater landforms caves and similar locations.

Subject: NELL:farm
Object: an area of land including various structures devoted primarily to the practice of producing and managing food (produce grains or livestock) fibres and increasingly fuel.

Subject: NELL:mountain
Object: A mountain is a landform that extends above the surrounding terrain in a limited area. A mountain is generally steeper than a hill but there is considerable overlap and usage often depends on local custom.

Subject: NELL:mountainrange
Object: A mountain range is a group of mountains bordered by lowlands or separated from other mountain ranges by passes or rivers.

Subject: NELL:building
Object: A building is a man-made structure designed for shelter or for continuous or periodic occupancy. All buildings are structures and therefore typed "Structure" which imparts other basic properties (see /architecture/structure). If something is not a structure it can't be typed as a building.  This category does not include complexes of individual buildings.

Subject: NELL:hospital
Object: A hospital is an institution for health care often but not always providing for longer-term patient stays.  All varieties of hospitals -- private public military etc. -- are included.

Subject: NELL:restaurant
Object: The restaurant type represents single restaurants as well as restaurant chains.

Subject: NELL:bridge
Object: A bridge is a structure across water valleys railway cuts areas of low elevation or other features which are difficult to cross.

Subject: NELL:hotel
Object: This type is intended to be used for hotels bed and breakfasts backpacker hostels or any other such place you might stay while travelling

Subject: NELL:airport
Object: A place where airplanes helicopters or other flying vehicles land and take off

Subject: NELL:placeofworship
Object: A place of worship is a building which is used by members of a religion for worship.

Subject: NELL:shoppingmall
Object: A shopping mall is a building or group of buildings containing many stores restaurants and businesses.

Subject: NELL:trainstation
Object: railway station (mainly British Commonwealth) or railroad station (mainly US)) is a railway facility where trains regularly stop to load or unload passengers or freight (goods). It generally consists of a platform next to the tracks and a building (depot) providing related services such as ticket sales and waiting rooms.

Subject: NELL:retailstore
Object: Brick & mortar retail stores and franchises. Retail means selling goods not services (e.g. prepared food)

Subject: NELL:agent
Object: a person or business authorized to act on another's behalf; a person or thing that acts or has the power to act; a natural force or object producing or used for obtaining specific results

Subject: NELL:animal
Object: A collection of common-sense animals more understandable to children than biologists.  It's OK to include both general kinds of animals such as bird but also common varieties of birds such as finch and robin. (FreeBase)  As with plant any mortal action upon an animal or action on a dead animal that results in something with a new name (e.g. milking shearing slaughtering or cooking it) results in something that is no longer an animal.

Subject: NELL:invertebrate
Object: An animal which does not have a back bone

Subject: NELL:mollusk
Object: invertebrate having a soft unsegmented body usually enclosed in a shell

Subject: NELL:arthropod
Object: Arthropods are members of the phylum Arthropoda.

Subject: NELL:insect
Object: class within the arthropods that have a chitinous exoskeleton a three-part body (head thorax and abdomen) three pairs of jointed legs compound eyes and two antennae

Subject: NELL:arachnid
Object: air-breathing arthropods characterized by simple eyes and four pairs of legs

Subject: NELL:crustacean
Object: form a very large group of arthropods usually treated as a subphylum which includes such familiar animals as crabs lobsters crayfish shrimp krill and barnacles. Like other arthropods crustaceans have an exoskeleton which they moult to grow. They are distinguished from other groups of arthropods such as insects myriapods and chelicerates by the possession of biramous (two-parted) limbs and by the nauplius form of the larvae.

Subject: NELL:vertebrate
Object: An animal which has a back bone

Subject: NELL:reptile
Object: Reptiles are animals in the (Linnaean) class Reptilia. They are characterized by breathing air laying tough-shelled amniotic eggs and having skin covered in scales and/or scutes.

Subject: NELL:bird
Object: Birds (class Aves) are winged bipedal endothermic (warm-blooded) egg-laying vertebrate animals.

Subject: NELL:fish
Object: A fish is any aquatic vertebrate animal that is covered with scales and equipped with two sets of paired fins and several unpaired fins. Most fish are "cold-blooded" or ectothermic allowing their body temperatures to vary as ambient temperatures change.

Subject: NELL:mammal
Object: Mammals (formally Mammalia) are a class of vertebrate air-breathing animals whose females are characterized by the possession of mammary glands while both males and females are characterized by hair and/or fur three middle ear bones used in hearing and a neocortex region in the brain.

Subject: NELL:amphibian
Object: Amphibians (class Amphibia from Amphi- meaning "on both sides" and -bios meaning "life") such as frogs salamanders and caecilians are ectothermic (or cold-blooded) animals that metamorphose from a juvenile water-breathing form either to an adult air-breathing form or to a paedomorph that retains some juvenile characteristics.

Subject: NELL:humanagent
Object: Those things to which we can ascribe agency that are composed of one or more humans

Subject: NELL:person
Object: A person is a human being (man woman or child) known to have actually existed. Living persons celebrities and politicians are persons as are deceased persons.

Subject: NELL:criminal
Object: a person who commits a crime

Subject: NELL:architect
Object: a person who designs buildings or other structures

Subject: NELL:politician
Object: Any person who has held or sought a position in a government. The term "politician" may not be strictly accurate for some positions such as kings but we have to call it something!

Subject: NELL:athlete
Object: An athlete is a person who plays a sport competitively.

Subject: NELL:male
Object: This category includes all male human beings.

Subject: NELL:writer
Object: A writer is a person who produces written work. This category includes book authors poets and playwrights.

Subject: NELL:professor
Object: A faculty member at a university or college

Subject: NELL:personbylocation
Object: Parent category to break up people by regional/national location which exists as a way to constrain some of the political predicates to the U.S.  For simplicity of decision-making we use "citizenship" as the rule for belongingness in these categories; this is probably "good enough" for what we want to do with the political predicates.

Subject: NELL:personnorthamerica
Object: citizens of countries in North America

Subject: NELL:personsouthamerica
Object: citizens of countries in South America

Subject: NELL:personantarctica
Object: Placeholder in case we change the definition of personByLocation categories such that there would be anyone to put here (there are no countries in Antarctica of which to be a citizen).

Subject: NELL:model
Object: a person who is paid to be a fashion model

Subject: NELL:astronaut
Object: An astronaut is a person that has flown in outer space. Not used for animals sent to space experimentally.

Subject: NELL:celebrity
Object: A celebrity is a person who is frequently featured in the media and is recognizable by the general public.

Subject: NELL:actor
Object: An actor is a person who performs in movies television plays or other forms of entertainment.

Subject: NELL:chef
Object: A chef is a professional cook.

Subject: NELL:comedian
Object: a person who makes a living by making you laugh

Subject: NELL:mlauthor
Object: A machine learning author is a person who has published research in the field of machine learning.

Subject: NELL:scientist
Object: A scientist is a professional who performs research to discover the rules which govern the natural world. This category includes mathematicians even though math isn't really a science.

Subject: NELL:visualartist
Object: A visual artist creates artistic works which are mainly experienced by sight. This category includes painters sculptors and architects but excludes authors.

Subject: NELL:coach
Object: A coach is a trainer for a sports team. He leads the team in exercises and manages the team during gameplay. This category includes assistant coaches and other trainers.

Subject: NELL:judge
Object: a judge in a court of law

Subject: NELL:monarch
Object: A monarch is a person who heads a monarchy such as a king or queen

Subject: NELL:female
Object: This category includes all female human beings.

Subject: NELL:musician
Object: A musician is a person who sings or plays a musical instrument as part of a musical act.

Subject: NELL:ceo
Object: A CEO is the chief executive officer of a company.

Subject: NELL:journalist
Object: Journalists are professionals who work in journalism. They collect and report news.

Subject: NELL:organization
Object: An organization is an organized body of members or people with a particular purpose; in the Freebase context a organization doesn't have a business association like a company.  Companies have their own type in the business domain located here.  In addition many types of organizations have their own more specialized co-types that give them additional properties.

Subject: NELL:nonprofitorganization
Object: A non-profit organization is a legally-constituted organization that does not make a profit from its operations.

Subject: NELL:musicartist
Object: An individual or a group that performs or makes music. Musical artists should typically have performed in front of an audience on a regular basis or have recorded musical tracks or musical albums. (FreeBase)

Subject: NELL:tradeunion
Object: A trade union (aka labor union) is an organization which represents workers in a certain industry or profession.

Subject: NELL:sportsteam
Object: A sports team is a group of athletes who play a sport together competitively

Subject: NELL:professionalorganization
Object: A professional organization is an organization of people who work in a particular field.

Subject: NELL:school
Object: A school is an organization whose primary function is education. This category includes universities K-12 schools and trade schools.

Subject: NELL:university
Object: A university is a post-high school educational institution. This category includes colleges and technical schools.

Subject: NELL:highschool
Object: Schools whose graduates would go directly on to universities vocational schools or other higher education.  No particular limit on age of incoming students.

Subject: NELL:geopoliticalorganization
Object: Those geopolitical entities that are organizations

Subject: NELL:politicsgroup
Object: Organizations which may or may not be part of the government that act in the arenas of politics or government.

Subject: NELL:governmentorganization
Object: A government is the organization or agency through which a political unit exercises its authority

Subject: NELL:nongovorganization
Object: Politically-active or governmentally-active organizations that are not part of the government including but not limited to some NGOs

Subject: NELL:politicalparty
Object: organized political group that primarily aims for the attainment of political power and public office for its designated members.

Subject: NELL:terroristorganization
Object: an organization that is involved in terrorist activities.

Subject: NELL:sportsleague
Object: A sports league is an association of teams that compete with each other in a sport. Sports leagues include conferences and divisions of other sports leagues.

Subject: NELL:company
Object: A company is an organization whose goal is to make money

Subject: NELL:automobilemaker
Object: A company that manufactures motor-powered vehicles (eg. cars motorcycles buses trucks and motorized bikes)

Subject: NELL:winery
Object: Companies that produce and sell wines

Subject: NELL:biotechcompany
Object: A company in a biotechnology field including pharmaceutical companies.

Subject: NELL:petroleumrefiningcompany
Object: a company in the petroleum sector

Subject: NELL:mediacompany
Object: Any company that deals in the production or marketing of media goods (film audio literature journalistic etc.)

Subject: NELL:magazine
Object: A magazine is a periodical bound typically published less frequently than daily. This includes electronic magazines. For lack of a better definitional boundary this therefore includes any periodical that is not instead a newspaper.

Subject: NELL:newspaper
Object: A newspaper is a periodical which is printed in a specific format (i.e. on newsprint) describes recent events and is typically published daily.

Subject: NELL:televisionstation
Object: A television station is a broadcaster which transmits television (audio & video).

Subject: NELL:recordlabel
Object: A record label is a company that releases music albums.

Subject: NELL:televisionnetwork
Object: Category for different types of TV networks (currently closed-world limited to major American networks)

Subject: NELL:radiostation
Object: A radio station is a broadcaster which transmits audio. This category includes broadcast radio satellite radio and internet radio stations.

Subject: NELL:bank
Object: Umbrella category for all kinds of banks

Subject: NELL:oilgasfield
Object: An field from which oil or natural gas are extracted.

Subject: NELL:item
Object: Any tangible thing that does not have the power to act (agency)

Subject: NELL:weapon
Object: A weapon is any tool used for fighting

Subject: NELL:automobileengine
Object: The engine type is to be used to classify specific powerplants used in an automobile. These may be year-specific but more frequently they often span multiple years models makes and generations.

Subject: NELL:drug
Object: A drug is a chemical substance that has or is reputed to have a phyisological effect on an organism. Medicinal herbal and illegal drugs can be included in this type.

Subject: NELL:personalcareitem
Object: Items used by people to care for their bodies or to maintain a certain appearance. Could also be called toiletries.

Subject: NELL:vehicle
Object: Any vessel or other conveyance machine used for purposes of travel. Apparel and other personal affects e.g. shoes or walking sticks do not count.

Subject: NELL:automobilemodel
Object: A model is a specific car carried under a make.

Subject: NELL:software
Object: software that runs on a computer.

Subject: NELL:videogame
Object: A video game is a piece of interactive software used primarily for entertainment including computer games console games arcade games and hand-held games. However this category excludes video game consoles.

Subject: NELL:mlsoftware
Object: A software package that offers machine learning functionality

Subject: NELL:clothing
Object: This type is for kinds of garments or clothing. For lack of a meaningful way to constrain this category through definition or existent sibling categories particularly when it comes to adorning the body for purposes of fashion (e.g. jewlery colored contact lenses costumery) or of utility (e.g. armor kneepads or other sports equipment corrective lenses) this will include anything wearable.

Subject: NELL:food
Object: A food is any edible substance with nutritional value whether it's a basic foodstuff like rice or apples or a commercial product like Poptarts or I Can't Believe It's Not Butter.  "Nutritional value" encompasses anything useful for growth or life such as water so long as the organism gets it through ingestion.

Subject: NELL:meat
Object: A type of animal flesh that is used as food. (Wikipedia)

Subject: NELL:condiment
Object: A sauce or seasoning added to food to impart a particular flavor or to complement the dish. (Wikipedia)

Subject: NELL:fruit
Object: A structure of a plant that contains its seeds. This is closer to the botanical definition than the cullinary / colloquial definition but is technically niether.

Subject: NELL:nut
Object: hard-shelled fruit of some plants having an indehiscent seed.

Subject: NELL:legume
Object: plant in the family Fabaceae (or Leguminosae) or a fruit of these specific plants. A legume fruit is a simple dry fruit that develops from a simple carpel and usually dehisces (opens along a seam) on two sides.

Subject: NELL:grain
Object: dry seed-like fruit produced by the cereal grasses: e.g. wheat barley Indian corn

Subject: NELL:candy
Object: A food which is made primarily of sugar and generally sold for wide distribution. This would include many dessert items like pie and cake that might not be strictly "candy" per se.

Subject: NELL:vegetable
Object: An edible plant or part of a plant other than a sweet fruit or seed. This usually means the leaf stem or root of a plant.  This is meant to dovetail with the more botanical definition we have of fruit and to not allow cullinary / colloquial vegetables that qualify for membership in our fruit category.  Mushrooms are not vegetables.

Subject: NELL:beverage
Object: A liquid meant for human consumption

Subject: NELL:wine
Object: Types of wines or specific vintanges of particular wineries

Subject: NELL:bakedgood
Object: A food which is made through baking in an oven

Subject: NELL:plant
Object: Member of kingdom plantae. A seed is considered to be a plant because it has been fertilized although the larger structure of a fruit which merely contains a seed is not itself a plant.  A picked flower such as a product sold as such is not a plant because it is something that has a new name as a result of a mortal action on a plant.

Subject: NELL:refineryproduct
Object: a product derived from a petroleum refinery

Subject: NELL:sportsequipment
Object: Anything which is used to play a sport

Subject: NELL:musicinstrument
Object: A Musical instrument is a device constructed or modified with the purpose of making music. In principle anything that produces sound and can somehow be controlled by a musician can serve as a musical instrument. (See e.g. the hardart.)

Subject: NELL:consumerelectronicitem
Object: An item intended for ordinary people that runs on electricity excluding appliances. This category includes accessories for consumer electronic items such as video games and DVDs.

Subject: NELL:videogamesystem
Object: includes any form of electronic game device from handheld units as small as a phone to large powerful computer systems and even arcade coin-operated systems.

Subject: NELL:bodypart
Object: Refers to any part of the human body. It can be either visible to the naked eye (gross anatomical structure) or microscopic.

Subject: NELL:muscle
Object: A muscle is a contractile form of tissue which animals use to effect movement.

Subject: NELL:vein
Object: A vein is a blood vessel that carries blood toward the heart.

Subject: NELL:bone
Object: a bone or bone structure in a vertebrate

Subject: NELL:nerve
Object: a single nerve cell or bundle of nerve cells

Subject: NELL:artery
Object: Arteries are muscular blood vessels that carry blood away from the heart.

Subject: NELL:lymphnode
Object: a lymph node in the body

Subject: NELL:braintissue
Object: any subregion of the brain but not including single nerves

Subject: NELL:officeitem
Object: Items usually found in an office that are used for clerical or intellectual work.

Subject: NELL:agriculturalproduct
Object: a living thing (or something derived therefrom) which is specifically cultivated and produced to sustain or enrich life

Subject: NELL:householditem
Object: Any item that could reasonably be found in or about a residence.

Subject: NELL:furniture
Object: Any functional or decorative mobile object with which a dwelling might be said to be "furnished" or any immobile variant of the same (such as an oven built into a wall).

Subject: NELL:flooritem
Object: Any item that is commonly found on the floor

Subject: NELL:bathroomitem
Object: Any item that is commonly found in a bathroom or restroom.

Subject: NELL:hallwayitem
Object: Any item that is commonly found in a hallway.

Subject: NELL:bedroomitem
Object: Any item that is commonly found in a bedroom.

Subject: NELL:tableitem
Object: Any item that is commonly found on a table.

Subject: NELL:kitchenitem
Object: Any item that might be found in a commercial or residential kitchen that is used for cullinary purposes or in pursuit of the same (e.g. a cupboard).

Subject: NELL:wallitem
Object: Any item that is commonly found on a wall

Subject: NELL:mediatype
Object: the means of communication as radio and television newspapers and magazines that reach or influence people widely

Subject: NELL:buildingfeature
Object: Any physical property or physical attribute that a building might have.

Subject: NELL:visualizablething
Object: something which can be recognized visually

Subject: NELL:color
Object: Color (or colour) is the visual perceptual property corresponding in humans to the categories called red yellow white etc.

Subject: NELL:geometricshape
Object: geometrical information that remains when location scale and rotational effects are filtered out from an object

Subject: NELL:visualizablescene
Object: a visual scene (for NEIL's scene classifiers)

Subject: NELL:abstractthing
Object: thought quality characteristic apart from concrete realities specific objects or actual instances; theoretical not applied or practical

Subject: NELL:protein
Object: Proteins are any complex organic compounds that consist of one or more chains of amino acids. Proteins are typically essential components of any living cell and indispensable to the proper functioning of all organisms.

Subject: NELL:hobby
Object: A hobby is an activity undertaken for pleasure in one's spare time. Some hobbies exist primarily as hobbies while others might be practiced professionally by some people but as hobbies by others.  This can include sport activities.

Subject: NELL:species
Object: is one of the basic units of biological classification and a taxonomic rank. A species is often defined as a group of organisms capable of interbreeding and producing fertile offspring.

Subject: NELL:virus
Object: A small infectious agent that replicates only inside the living cells of other organisms

Subject: NELL:bacteria
Object: single-celled or noncellular spherical or spiral or rod-shaped organisms lacking chlorophyll that reproduce by fission;

Subject: NELL:archaea
Object: single-celled organisms lacking nuclei formerly called archaebacteria but now known to differ fundamentally from bacteria

Subject: NELL:profession
Object: The career or job which a person performs for most of their working life or for which they are best known (FreeBase)

Subject: NELL:jobposition
Object: Positions are job titles or named roles within an organization. Examples include "CEO" "President" "mayor" "vice president for research" "sergeant" etc. They do not include generic activities or career terms like "pianist" "researcher" "scientist" etc.

Subject: NELL:religion
Object: Religious sects denominations and (meta-)organizations. NOT church buildings or individual chapters/institutions.

Subject: NELL:chemical
Object: A chemical compound is a molecular substance consisting of multiple atoms which are bonded together by a chemical reaction. This type can be used for compounds made of the same element (e.g. allotropes) or multiple different elements. Compounds are different from chemical mixtures because mixtures can be mixed and separated physically without a reaction; The elements of the periodic table

Subject: NELL:date
Object: a particular month day and year at which some event happened or will happen; the time or period to which any event or thing belongs; period in general

Subject: NELL:dayofweek
Object: Seven named days of the week

Subject: NELL:victim
Object: a victim of an event could be a person or a group of person like childrens students soldiers drivers etc

Subject: NELL:game
Object: General parent category for more specific kinds of games

Subject: NELL:sportsgame
Object: A sports game is a particular instance of a sporting event where teams or athletes compete. This could be a series of matches if the competitors remain the same but this does not extend to something like a tournament or season where the series of matches draws on different combinations from a set of teams.

Subject: NELL:traditionalgame
Object: Includes all non-sports non-electronic games including board games parlor games and card games.

Subject: NELL:boardgame
Object: Games played with physical pieces on a board (electronic games not allowed)

Subject: NELL:parlourgame
Object: Parlour games drawing room games car games and similar passtimes that are not card games dice games board games etc.

Subject: NELL:cardgame
Object: Games that are played with only a physical deck of cards (electronic games not allowed)

Subject: NELL:sport
Object: A game which involves some form of physical prowess (i.e. athleticism as opposed to the physical prowess needed for a parlour game like Pin the Tail on the Donkey).  Note that this does not include non-game sports; those may be hobbies instead.

Subject: NELL:emotion
Object: Emotion is the complex psychophysiological experience of an individual's state of mind as interacting with biochemical (internal) and environmental (external) influences

Subject: NELL:currency
Object: A currency is money that is used (or has been used) as a medium of exchange

Subject: NELL:recipe
Object: A recipe is a method of preparing a dish. Dishes may have multiple recipes. For instance there may be many different recipes for chocolate chip cookies.

Subject: NELL:event
Object: An event is a topic that can be described by the time or date at which it happened. Long-lasting events may be described as occurring between two dates. It is sometimes appropriate to create abstract events as collections of other events

Subject: NELL:conference
Object: A conference is a regular or recurring meeting of people to "confer" about a topic. It may take many forms.

Subject: NELL:mlconference
Object: A conference in the area of machine learning

Subject: NELL:election
Object: An opportunity for constituents to vote for a political party or candidate for a governmental office or seat or the ability to run for a governmental office or seat (as is the case with primaries). (FreeBase)

Subject: NELL:convention
Object: a large meeting such as the Star Trek Convention

Subject: NELL:personhiredbyorganization
